                <position place="tail" book_orientation="0">
                    <marginalia_text> 
                        Livij Epitomen L. Florus contraxit: et alterum habemus Flori opusculum de Romana historia: quo nihil potest fingi in illo genere vel 
                        acutius, vel lepidius. Censura acerrimi critici, l. 5. de trad. discipl. Res populi Romani ut scit&egrave; a L. Floro traduntur, non 
                        min&ugrave;s gentis historiam complectuntur, sed orbis universi, et totius generis humani. Idem ibidem, tam graviter, quam breviter. 
                        Unus Florus, instar Eutropij, et Justini: Aurelij Victoris, et Aemilij Probi.
                    </marginalia_text>
                <person name="Florus"/>
                <person name="Flavius Eutropius"/>
                <person name="Justin"/>
                <person name="Aurelius Victor"/>
                <person name="Aemilius Probus"/>
                <book title="Epitome de T. Livio Bellorum omnium annorum DCC Libri duo"/>
                <book title="De gestis Romanorum libri IIII"/> <!--JG: Not entirely sure-->
                <book title="De disciplinis libri XX"/>
                <book title="Ab Urbe Condita"/>
                </position>
            </language>
            <translation>
                "Lucius Florus compiled an Epitome of Livy; we also have another small work about Roman history by Florus. And in this genre nothing can be 
                composed that is more astute or entertaining.‚Äù The assessment of the most penetrating critic [Juan Luis Vives] in bk. 5 of 'De trandendis 
                disciplinis'. The affairs of the Roman people, as skilfully handed down by Lucius Florus, cover not only the history of a nation, but of the 
                complete world, and the entire human race. In that very text the same person [writes] equally impressively as concisely. Florus alone is equal
                to Eutropius and Justin, to Aurelius Victor and Aemilius Probus.
            </translation>
        </marginalia>
        
